He considered the difference between the two movies on each feature (e.g. if Movie A was 90% romantic and Movie B was only 10%, that's a difference of 80 percentage points), and then weighed those differences t
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between movies in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: how suspenseful the movie was, how artistic it was, and how action-packed it was. He checked which movie was better on each feature (i.e. which movie 'won' on each feature), and chose the movie that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
strategy: My favorite movies are comedies, so "funny" was an important category to me. I tried to stay away from movies that were "violent, artistic, and dramatic" without any "funny" because they sounded very serious. "Violence" in general is not my favorite, but I will tolerate it for the sake of "funny" or "action-packed". "Science fiction" versus "fantasy" didn't really matter to me, and "romance" is a good thing but not critical in my decisions. Also, sometimes I chose just based on which moves has overall better ratings. For example, if Movie A had less than 40% in every category, but Movie B had plenty of categories above 70%, I figured Movie B would just be more interesting no matter what it was about.
strategy2: It hasn't changed. I took many categories into consideration for each choice, and weighed combinations and amounts differently, looking at the movie holistically to determine which one I'd rather watch.
metastrategy: We were instructed at the beginning of Section 1 to pay attention to our decision making process, so I noted on the first few trials which things were most important to me and which things I didn't like but could overlook.

strategy: First I looked at if the movie was rated as violent because I knew it would have more action. After the violence, I looked equally at suspense and action-packed to either confirm or deny my feelings. Additionally, I looked at dramatic and funny. I went in the order that I described and chose the movie with the highest rating in these 4 domains. Sometimes my method would not work, but In those cases I would do a more wholistic approach and try and see which one I felt was still on course for what I wanted.
strategy2: I took into account every variable with a different desire for each. In my mind, I knew I would account for violence, action-packed, and suspense in their own manner, but I wanted them to be high. But, that doesn't mean I disqualified the other areas. I looked at all of them as a holistic approach.
metastrategy: I determined in over the course of section 1. It took me the first 5-10 to determine which aspects I liked the most, and then after that, I was very confident in picking the movie I desired every time.

He considered the difference between the two movies on each feature (e.g. if Movie A was 90% romantic and Movie B was only 10%, that's a difference of 80 percentage points), and then weighed those differences t
strategy: I first evaluated the violence in each selection, and then weighed funny, dramatic, suspensful, and action packed.  If the two films were close in the later categories but much different in the violence category, I chose the less violent film.  I also tried to avoid anything too artistic unless the other choice was high in violence and lower in the other four previously mentioned categories.  Sometimes I chose high violence because the other film was so low rated in all other categories (did not seem to appeal to anyone) or because it is had a very high artistic rating.  I do not mind artistic themes/cinematograohy/story line, but I do not want anything overly abstact.  If I had to balance violence vs artistic, and the other categories were pretty even in each selection, I chose the more artistic film.  Overall, I enjoy sci-fi and fantasy, so I leaned towards those unless they were too artistic or violent.  When chosing between two that were close in thier categories, a higher funny rating would win out over a romantic rating.  I did not avoid romantic movies, but it was not an influencing factor one way or the other.
strategy2: It has not changed.  I had two items - violence and artistic - that I weighed, with violence being weighed more heavily.  I then looked to other ratings I value - funny, action packed, fantasy, drama, suspensful, sci-fi, to see if there was a clear winner.  I tried to avoid violence unless the other film was very high in artisitc, or clearly won the other categories.  A preference for low violence almost always won, followed by a mid-low artistic rating. If those items were near equal, I relied on the other items.  If they were unequal, but one film scored very low in all other categories, I would chose the overall better rated film, regardless of violence or artistic rating.
metastrategy: I evaluated my thought process and strategy, compared them to the examples of styles given, and was able to see my strategy refleted (for the most part) in the exapmles given.  I was aware of my process while performing section 1 and did so thoughfully, so the section 2 questions just put them into other terms/words.
